REPORT 4 — Saudi Aramco SACS‑002 Third‑Party Risk Assessment (TPRA)
Title: Third‑Party Risk Assessment of Cloud‑Based Maintenance Management Vendor — SACS‑002 Compliance Review
Region: Middle East (Saudi Arabia)
Industry: Energy / Critical Infrastructure
Author: Ssambra — Identity Auditor & Threat Sentinel

1. Executive Summary
A Saudi energy operator engaged a cloud‑based maintenance management vendor to support refinery operations. During onboarding, the vendor failed to meet several Saudi Aramco Cybersecurity Standard (SACS‑002) requirements, including:

Delayed incident notification capability

Weak identity governance

No evidence of data localization controls

Insufficient logging and monitoring

This Third‑Party Risk Assessment evaluates the vendor’s compliance posture, identifies gaps, and provides remediation guidance aligned with SACS‑002 and regional expectations for critical infrastructure.

2. Background
Saudi Aramco requires all third‑party vendors supporting operational technology (OT) or sensitive business functions to comply with SACS‑002, a cybersecurity standard covering:

Governance

Access control

Network security

Incident response

Data protection

Logging and monitoring

The vendor provides a SaaS platform used by refinery engineers to track maintenance tasks, equipment failures, and safety inspections.

Your role:

Conduct a SACS‑002‑aligned TPRA

Identify compliance gaps

Assess operational risk

Recommend corrective actions

3. Scope
This assessment covers:

Vendor governance and cybersecurity maturity

Identity and access management

Data residency and protection

Incident response readiness

Logging and monitoring

Contractual obligations under SACS‑002

4. Assessment Methodology
Reviewed vendor policies, SOC 2 report, and architecture diagrams

Conducted interviews with vendor security lead

Evaluated platform configuration in staging environment

Mapped findings to SACS‑002 control domains

Assessed risk severity and likelihood

5. Key Findings (Mapped to SACS‑002)
Finding 1 — Incident Notification Not Within 24 Hours
SACS‑002 Requirement:  
Vendors must notify Aramco of any security incident within 24 hours.

Issue:  
Vendor’s policy states 72‑hour notification window.

Risk:  
Delayed containment of OT‑related incidents.

Severity: High
Likelihood: Medium

Finding 2 — Weak Identity Governance
SACS‑002 Requirement:

Unique user IDs

MFA for all privileged accounts

Quarterly access reviews

Issue:

MFA optional for standard users

No documented access review process

Shared admin account used by support team

Risk:  
Unauthorized access to refinery maintenance data.

Severity: High
Likelihood: High

Finding 3 — No Data Residency Controls
SACS‑002 Requirement:  
Critical infrastructure data must be stored in approved regions.

Issue:  
Vendor stores data in EU and U.S. regions with no localization option.

Risk:  
Regulatory non‑compliance; geopolitical exposure.

Severity: High
Likelihood: Medium

Finding 4 — Insufficient Logging & Monitoring
SACS‑002 Requirement:  
Vendors must maintain logs for at least 12 months and provide them upon request.

Issue:

Logs retained for only 30 days

No export mechanism

No SIEM integration

Risk:  
Inability to investigate incidents or support forensic analysis.

Severity: Medium
Likelihood: High

Finding 5 — No Evidence of Secure SDLC
SACS‑002 Requirement:  
Vendors must follow a secure development lifecycle with code review and vulnerability scanning.

Issue:  
Vendor provided no documentation of:

Static code analysis

Dependency scanning

Penetration testing

Risk:  
Unknown vulnerabilities in SaaS platform.

Severity: Medium
Likelihood: Medium

6. Cultural & Regional Considerations (Your “Bridge” Value)
Your experience working with Middle Eastern clients allows you to highlight:

The importance of trust and transparency in vendor relationships

The expectation of rapid communication during incidents

The cultural emphasis on clear accountability and chain of command

The need for data sovereignty due to geopolitical sensitivities

This positions you as a compliance professional who understands both technical controls and regional business norms.

7. Recommendations
Governance
Update incident response policy to 24‑hour notification

Establish quarterly access review process

Provide secure SDLC documentation

Technical
Enforce MFA for all users

Eliminate shared admin accounts

Implement 12‑month log retention

Enable SIEM integration

Data Protection
Provide region‑locked storage

Implement encryption key management aligned with SACS‑002

Contractual
Update SLA to include:

Residency requirements

Log retention

Incident notification

Audit rights

